name: Approaching the Green Sand Beach, Hawaii
description:
ALL PRINTS SHIP FREE!!! Yes, FREE!

This is the view as you approach my favorite beach in the U.S! Papakolea Beach is located in South Point Park on the island of Hawaii. The beach is a rough yet beautifully sculpted cinder cone styled beach with the infamous green sand and beautiful clear blue waters.

Papakōlea Beach is located in a bay half circled by Puʻu Mahana, a cinder cone formed over 49,000 years ago and associated with the southwest rift of Mauna Loa. Since its last eruption, the cinder cone has partially collapsed and been partially eroded by the ocean.

The source of the green coloration of the beach sands is due to  olivine crystals which are winnowed from the eroding headland by the action of the sea. Olivine, being denser and tougher than the ash fragments, glass and black pyroxene of the rest of the rocks and lava flows, tends to accumulate on the beach whereas the usual volcanic sand is swept out to sea. Although these crystals are eventually washed away as well, the constant erosion of the cinder cone ensures a steady supply of sand for the foreseeable future—eventually, however, the supply will run out and the beach will look like any other.

description:

This photograph caught an elusive baby Ghost Crab in between it's amazing 10mph sprints between the sand and the surf. This little guy was no bigger than my big toenail! He stopped for an instant I clicked the shutter got the shot and poof, as quick as he arrived he was gone! I couldn't help but laugh aloud because at the time I had no idea a crab that small could run SO fast!

Here is a small paragraph talking about ghost crabs:

"Anyone who spends time enjoying Hawaii’s beautiful sand beaches becomes familiar with a common inhabitant: the ghost crab. An encounter with a ghost crab may consist of only a fleeting glimpse, much like seeing a ghost, because these little crabs are among the world’s fastest creatures. Compared to a sprinting cheetah traveling a certain number of body lengths in a given time frame, a ghost crab can travel 10 times the number of body lengths as a cheetah in the same period, making it arguably “faster”— or so claim some researchers."

Read more about Ghost Crabs here:

http://www.mauioceancenter.com/marinepdf/ghost_crabs.pdf
